entions to advance women's sexual, social, political, and economic rights. Despite these accomplishments, we find ourselves at an ever more difficult juncture in the struggle to fully realize women's rights as human rights. Complications, such as terrorism and the "war" against it, the HIV/AIDS pandemic, the incursion of religious fundamentalism into governments, and the U.S. government's retreat from the international agenda on sexual and reproductive rights have raised questions about the direction of policy implementations and have prevented straightforward progress. This timely collection brings together eight wide-reaching and provocative essays that examine the practical and theoretical issues of sexual and reproductive health policy and implementation.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aBirth controlxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aContraceptionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aHuman rights. 0aReproductive health. 0aWomen's rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aChandiramani, Radhika1 aChavkin, Wendy1 aChavkin, Wendy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChesler, Ellen1 aChesler, Ellen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Martha1 aHorn, Jessica1 aImam, Ayesha1 aKeijzer, Benno De1 aOrtiz-Ortega, Adriana1 aRichey, Lisa Ann1 aRobinson, Mary1 aWinckler, Edwin08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541181423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813541181.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKAL